10. HTTP(S) Load Balancer with Cloud Armor
Deploy an HTTP(S) Load Balancer and configure a Cloud Armor security policy to
protect backend services from unauthorized access (2).
Elastic Google Cloud Infrastructure: Scaling and Automation
Lab: Configure an application load balancer with autoscaling


✅ 10. HTTP(S) Load Balancer with Cloud Armor (Step-by-Step)

🎯 Goal:

Create HTTP Load Balancer
Configure Managed Instance Groups (MIG) with autoscaling
Add Cloud Armor security policy to protect backend
🔹 Step 0: Start Lab
Click Start Lab
Open Google Cloud Console
Login with lab credentials
Accept terms → Skip 2FA
🔹 Step 1: Create Firewall Rule (Health Check)

Go to:

VPC Network → Firewall
Click Create Firewall Rule
Enter:
Name: fw-allow-health-checks
Network: default
Target tags: allow-health-checks

Source IPv4 ranges:

130.211.0.0/22
35.191.0.0/16
Protocols: tcp:80
Click Create

✅ Allows Google health checks

🔹 Step 2: Create Cloud NAT

Go to:

Network Services → Cloud NAT
Click Get Started
Configure:
NAT Name: nat-config
Network: default
Region: (Lab Region)
Click Create new router
Name: nat-router
Click Create

⏳ Wait until status = Running

🔹 Step 3: Create Web Server VM

Go to:

Compute Engine → VM Instances
Click Create Instance
Configure:
Name: webserver
Region/Zone: Lab values
Network tag: allow-health-checks
External IP: None
Click Create
🔸 Install Apache
Click SSH
Run:
sudo apt-get update
sudo apt-get install -y apache2
sudo service apache2 start
Enable auto start:
sudo update-rc.d apache2 enable
Test:
curl localhost
🔹 Step 4: Create Custom Image

Go to:

Compute Engine → VM Instances
Select VM → Click Delete (keep disk)

Go to:

Compute Engine → Images
Click Create Image
Enter:
Name: mywebserver
Source: Disk → webserver
Click Create
🔹 Step 5: Create Instance Template

Go to:

Compute Engine → Instance Templates
Click Create Template
Configure:
Name: mywebserver-template
Machine: e2-micro
Boot disk: Custom image → mywebserver
Network tag: allow-health-checks
External IP: None
Click Create
🔹 Step 6: Create Health Check

Go to:

Compute Engine → Health Checks
Click Create
Enter:
Name: http-health-check
Protocol: TCP
Port: 80
Click Create
🔹 Step 7: Create Managed Instance Groups (MIG)
👉 MIG 1

Go to:

Compute Engine → Instance Groups
Click Create
Configure:
Name: us-1-mig
Template: mywebserver-template
Region: Region 1
Autoscaling:
Min: 1
Max: 2
CPU/HTTP LB: 80%
Health check: http-health-check
Click Create
👉 MIG 2

Repeat same:

Name: notus-1-mig
Region: Region 2
🔹 Step 8: Create HTTP Load Balancer

Go to:

Network Services → Load Balancing
Click Create Load Balancer
Choose:
Application Load Balancer
External
Global
🔸 Frontend Config
Protocol: HTTP
IP: Ephemeral
Port: 80
🔸 Backend Config
Create backend:
Name: http-backend
Add:
us-1-mig
notus-1-mig
Port: 80
Health check: http-health-check
Enable logging
🔸 Finalize
Name: http-lb
Click Create

⏳ Wait for IP

🔹 Step 9: Test Load Balancer
Open:
http://<LOAD_BALANCER_IP>
You should see:
👉 Apache default page
🔹 Step 10: Stress Test
Create VM:
Name: stress-test
SSH → run:
ab -n 500000 -c 1000 http://<LB_IP>/

👉 Observe:

Traffic distributed
Autoscaling triggered
🔹 Step 11: Configure Cloud Armor (IMPORTANT)

👉 This is the security part (extra for your question)

Go to:

Network Security → Cloud Armor
Click Create Security Policy
Enter:
Name: block-policy
Add Rule:
Priority: 1000

Condition:

IP Address = (your test IP or deny all)
Action: Deny (403)
Save
🔸 Attach to Backend

Go to:

Load Balancer → Backend Service
Edit backend

Attach:

Security Policy → block-policy
Save
🔹 Step 12: Verify Cloud Armor
Try accessing LB again
If blocked → shows 403 Forbidden

✅ Protection working

🎯 Key Concepts (Exam Important)
Load Balancer distributes traffic globally
MIG provides autoscaling
Health check ensures instance health
Cloud NAT allows outbound traffic
Cloud Armor protects from attacks (DDoS, IP block)
📌 Architecture Flow
User → Load Balancer → Backend (MIG) → VM
                  ↓
             Cloud Armor
⚡ Final Summary

✔ Firewall → Allow health check
✔ NAT → Outbound internet
✔ VM → Apache server
✔ Image → Template → MIG
✔ Load Balancer → Traffic distribution
✔ Cloud Armor → Security
